            "date": "2017-05-02T17:06:15Z",
            "logo": null,
            "enclosures": null,
            "content": "<p>Brian Barrett, writing for Wired:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Although the hack offers a reminder that even the best security\ncan be undone by the so-called \u201cweakest link\u201d &#8212; Netflix can\u2019t\ndo much if a vendor is compromised &#8212; it provides a bigger\nlesson in how the internet has largely shifted away from\ntorrenting. If a show lands on The Pirate Bay and nobody\nwatches, did it really stream?</p>\n\n<p>Consider that in 2011, BitTorrent accounted for 23 percent of\ndaily internet traffic in North America, according to\nnetwork-equipment company Sandvine. By last year, that number sat\nat under 5 percent. \u201cThere\u2019s always going to be the floor of\npeople that are always going to be torrenting,\u201d says Sandvine\nspokesperson Dan Deeth. That group will surely enjoy whatever\nPiper\u2019s up to in season five. But the idea that so small a cohort\nmight prompt Netflix to negotiate with hackers seems absurd.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>I agree with this: Netflix&#8217;s best defenses against piracy are the facts that the actual Netflix service is so affordable and so convenient to use. The same thing happened with the iTunes Music Store back in the day.</p>\n\n<div>\n<a  title=\"Permanent link to \u2018The &#8216;Orange Is the New Black&#8217; Netflix Hack Was a Terrible Idea\u2019\"  href=\"https://daringfireball.net/linked/2017/05/02/orange-is-the-new-black-hack\">&nbsp;\u2605&nbsp;</a>\n</div>",
            "link": "https://www.wired.com/2017/05/orange-is-the-new-black-leak/?utm_content=buffer99966&utm_medium=social&utm_source=twitter.com&utm_campaign=buffer",
            "author": "John Gruber",
            "tags": [
              "The Pirate Bay",
              "Suprnova.org",
              "Internet",
              "North America",
              "IPhone",
              "BitTorrent",
              "ITunes",
              "Comparison of BitTorrent sites"
            ],
            "title": "The \u2018Orange Is the New Black\u2019 Netflix Hack Was a Terrible Idea",
            "summary": "Although the hack offers a reminder that even the best security\ncan be undone by the so-called \u201cweakest link\u201d \u2014 Netflix can\u2019t\ndo much if a vendor is compromised \u2014 it provides a bigger\nlesson in how the internet has largely shifted away from\ntorrenting. Consider that in 2011, BitTorrent accounted for 23 percent of\ndaily internet traffic in North America, according to\nnetwork-equipment company Sandvine. I agree with this: Netflix\u2019s best defenses against piracy are the facts that the actual Netflix service is so affordable and so convenient to use."
